<p>Iran remains under a nationwide internet blackout as accounts and videos emerging despite restrictions describe a lethal crackdown on the country’s latest wave of protests. Multiple reports cite exceptionally high casualty estimates, with TIME citing local health officials suggesting the death toll could exceed 30,000, including claims of tens of thousands killed over two days. In a notable sign of internal debate, Yousef Pezeshkian—son of Iran’s president and a government adviser—publicly urged authorities to restore connectivity, arguing the shutdown deepens public anger and postpones accountability for violence shown in images and video.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/z8NHtoZavoTHoFXPvBhGwRd0YwMQFBT6iY3Zol5ywXSJ1dFiAwOqnStTAriLIlj966R6d-4WkghFffDbYEyK0bKNH_FpuxOJt_9Rs0EzpnUFIKZrgM0VyB7lbYKvLOooewQ8QmP3RnIWntUi5jSTVQCnZ0lx2iWWN2kl2P7msFaISkWS5IETVeaEEVhbp9UZaBOVz-zVfoA' alt='Tehran in October, before the internet crackdown.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Communications squeeze: Protests erupted amid a communications blackout, with outside reporting relying on fragments of video and witness testimony that filter out despite restrictions.</li><li>Street-level security: In multiple cities, heavily armed security forces patrol streets after the crackdown, while day-to-day commerce has been disrupted and businesses struggle to operate.</li><li>Medical signal: RFE/RL’s live coverage cited a hospital director reporting a sudden surge in eye injuries, a pattern often associated with crowd-control munitions during unrest.</li><li>Diaspora anxiety: Iranians living in the United States told The Guardian they feel anxious and helpless watching events unfold from afar, and they weighed the risks of possible U.S. involvement.</li><li>Connectivity flickers: Even under the two-week blackout, some Iranians have experienced brief and unexplained windows of internet access, widening what can be documented and shared.</li></ul><blockquote>Keeping the internet shut will create dissatisfaction and widen the gap between the people and the government - Yousef Pezeshkian</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Yousef Pezeshkian (president’s son, government adviser): He urged authorities to restore internet access, warning the prolonged shutdown will worsen anti-government sentiment and deepen the rift between society and the state. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jan/25/iran-presidents-son-urges-authorities-to-restore-internet-after-protest-blackout'>The Guardian</a>)</li><li>Iranian government/security forces (as described by reporters): The state maintained severe restrictions and a security-heavy posture after protests, with reporting describing a violent crackdown and continuing limits on communications. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/25/world/middleeast/iran-how-crackdown-was-done.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Local health officials cited by TIME: Two senior health ministry officials told TIME the death toll could surpass 30,000, including very high claims for a two-day period in January. (<a href='https://time.com/7357635/more-than-30000-killed-in-iran-say-senior-officials/'>TIME</a>)</li><li>Iranians abroad (diaspora in the U.S.): Some Iranians in the United States described emotional distress and uncertainty, and debated whether external pressure or intervention would help or worsen the situation. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jan/25/iran-us-protests-crackdown'>The Guardian</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jan/25/iran-us-protests-crackdown'>‘Emotionally devastating’: Iranians in US on regime’s deadly protest crackdown</a> - theguardian.com</li><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/25/world/middleeast/iran-how-crackdown-was-done.html'>How Iran Crushed a Citizen Uprising With Lethal Force</a> - nytimes.com</li><li><a href='https://time.com/7357635/more-than-30000-killed-in-iran-say-senior-officials/'>Iran Prote